<doc id="213671" wikidata="Q725944" url="?curid=213671" title="Runge–Kutta methods">
<text>In numerical analysis, the Runge–Kutta methods ( ) are a family of implicit and explicit iterative methods, which include the Euler method, used in temporal discretization for the approximate solutions of simultaneous nonlinear equations. These methods were developed around 1900 by the German mathematicians Carl Runge and Wilhelm Kutta.

==The Runge–Kutta method==
The most widely known member of the Runge–Kutta family is generally referred to as &quot;RK4&quot;, the &quot;classic Runge–Kutta method&quot; or simply as &quot;the Runge–Kutta method&quot;.

Let an initial value problem be specified as follows:

:formula_1

Here formula_2 is an unknown function (scalar or vector) of time formula_3, which we would like to approximate; we are told that formula_4, the rate at which formula_2 changes, is a function of formula_3 and of formula_2 itself. At the initial time formula_8 the corresponding formula_2 value is formula_10. The function formula_11 and the initial conditions formula_8, formula_10 are given.

Now we pick a step-size &quot;h&quot; &gt; 0 and define:

:formula_14

for &quot;n&quot; = 0, 1, 2, 3, ..., using
:formula_15
(&quot;Note: the above equations have different but equivalent definitions in different texts.&quot;)

Here formula_16 is the RK4 approximation of formula_17, and the next value (formula_16) is determined by the present value (formula_19) plus the weighted average of four increments, where each increment is the product of the size of the interval, &quot;h&quot;, and an estimated slope specified by function &quot;f&quot; on the right-hand side of the differential equation.
* formula_20 is the slope at the beginning of the interval, using formula_21 (Euler&#x27;s method);
* formula_22 is the slope at the midpoint of the interval, using formula_21 and formula_24;
* formula_25 is again the slope at the midpoint, but now using formula_21 and formula_27;
* formula_28 is the slope at the end of the interval, using formula_21 and formula_30.

In averaging the four slopes, greater weight is given to the slopes at the midpoint. If formula_11 is independent of formula_2, so that the differential equation is equivalent to a simple integral, then RK4 is Simpson&#x27;s rule.

The RK4 method is a fourth-order method, meaning that the local truncation error is on the order of formula_33, while the total accumulated error is on the order of formula_34.

In many practical applications the function formula_11 is independent of formula_3 (so called autonomous system, or time-invariant system, especially in physics), and their increments are not computed at all and not passed to function formula_11, with only the final formula for formula_38 used.

==Explicit Runge–Kutta methods==
The family of explicit Runge–Kutta methods is a generalization of the RK4 method mentioned above. It is given by
:formula_39
where
:formula_40
:(&quot;Note: the above equations may have different but equivalent definitions in some texts.&quot;)

To specify a particular method, one needs to provide the integer &quot;s&quot; (the number of stages), and the coefficients &quot;aij&quot; (for 1 ≤ &quot;j&quot; &lt; &quot;i&quot; ≤ &quot;s&quot;), &quot;bi&quot; (for &quot;i&quot; = 1, 2, ..., &quot;s&quot;) and &quot;ci&quot; (for &quot;i&quot; = 2, 3, ..., &quot;s&quot;). The matrix [&quot;aij&quot;] is called the &quot;Runge–Kutta matrix&quot;, while the &quot;bi&quot; and &quot;ci&quot; are known as the &quot;weights&quot; and the &quot;nodes&quot;. These data are usually arranged in a mnemonic device, known as a &quot;Butcher tableau&quot; (after John C. Butcher):

A Taylor series expansion shows that the Runge–Kutta method is consistent if and only if
:formula_41
There are also accompanying requirements if one requires the method to have a certain order &quot;p&quot;, meaning that the local truncation error is O(&quot;hp&quot;+1). These can be derived from the definition of the truncation error itself. For example, a two-stage method has order 2 if &quot;b&quot;1 + &quot;b&quot;2 = 1, &quot;b&quot;2&quot;c&quot;2 = 1/2, and &quot;b&quot;2&quot;a&quot;21 = 1/2. Note that a popular condition for determining coefficients is 
:formula_42
This condition alone, however, is neither sufficient, nor necessary for consistency.
In general, if an explicit formula_43-stage Runge–Kutta method has order formula_44, then it can be proven that the number of stages must satisfy formula_45 and if formula_46, then formula_47.
However, it is not known whether these bounds are &quot;sharp&quot; in all cases. In some cases, it is proven that the bound cannot be achieved. For instance, Butcher proved that for formula_48, there is no explicit method with formula_49 stages. Butcher also proved that for formula_50, there is no explicit Runge-Kutta method with formula_51 stages. In general, however, it remains an open problem what the precise minimum number of stages formula_43 is for an explicit Runge–Kutta method to have order formula_44. Some values which are known are:
:formula_54
The provable bound above then imply that we can not find methods of orders formula_55 that require fewer stages than the methods we already know for these orders. The work of Butcher also proves that 7th and 8th order methods have a minimum of 9 and 11 stages, respectively. An example of an explicit method of order 6 with 7 stages can be found in Ref. Explicit methods of order 7 with 9 stages and explicit methods of order 8 with 11 stages are also known. See Refs. for a summary.

